label: University of Pennsylvania Ms. Codex 1090: Apologia cuiusdam regiae famae studiosi
attribution: Provided by the University of Pennsylvania Libraries
description:
Summary: A copy of the pamphlet printed in 1551 in Paris by Charles Estienne defending Henry II of France, whom the German emperor's publicists had blamed for betraying Christian Europe by seeking the help of the Turkish sultan against Charles V.
        Language: Latin
        Support: paper
        Extent: 
        Collation: Paper, i + 14 + i; 1-3⁴ 4²; modern pencil foliation, lower right recto.
        Layout: Written in 28 long lines.
        Script: Written in a humanistic script.
        Decoration: 
        Binding: Modern paper boards.
        Origin: Written in France in the second half of the 16th century (Zacour-Hirsch).
        Cite as:	
        UPenn Ms. Codex 1090
        For catalog record, see Permanent Link: 4237686 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/4237686
  For TEI description and digital images, see: http://openn.library.upenn.edu/Data/PennManuscripts/html/mscodex1090.html
